\b Gombey
\b0  is an iconic symbol of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bermuda"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 Bermuda}}, this {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Folklife"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 folklife}} tradition reflecting the island\'92s blend of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ethnic_groups_of_Africa"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 African}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 indigenous peoples}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caribbean"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 Caribbean}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Kingdom"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 British}} cultures, incorporating them over time into a unique performance art full of colourful and intricate masquerade, dance and drumming.\
Dancers are usually male, and perform in groups of 10-30 though in modern times female groups have emerged. The traditions have been passed down orally from one generation to the next within families and the Captains of each troupe determine the direction of the troupe and style that is taught. Thus within troupes there can be found subtle but distinct differences in beats, dances, costumes, headdresses, by which they can each be recognised.\
